# No backward compatibility (default)

Internal tooling—not a versioned public API. Unless the user explicitly asks for backward compatibility or a migration path, assume none is required.

## Clean implementation

- Implement and document the **current** design only.
- Rename identifiers, files, functions, and docs to match the new approach; update all references in the same change.
- Remove superseded code, config keys, and docs — do not leave aliases, wrappers, or parallel paths.

## Do not add unless requested

- Prose or comments such as "previously", "formerly", "replaces", migration guides, or changelog-style history.
- Dual naming (`oldX` / `newX`), deprecated aliases, or comments explaining the old design.
- Commented-out old code kept "for reference".

## Explicit confirmation

When the user says "no backward compatibility", "clean break", "full rename", or similar, treat that as confirmation—execute a full replacement without asking again.

## When to ask first

Before **large** changes, ask whether backward compatibility matters if the change affects:

- `./wsl-builder.sh` / `./wsl-stacker.sh` CLI or stack file formats
- `wsl-builds.conf` keys (users may have local gitignored configs)
- Cross-build renames or entrypoints with many touch points

For deeper refactor checklists, see [no-backward-compatibility/SKILL.md](../skills/no-backward-compatibility/SKILL.md).
